comments.body:
@rjb4standards, 
using the picture @OR13 provided above,
- A producer creates a **statement** about an artifact
- When a producer **signed the statement** (issuer of a cert, signed by an identity)
- A **transparent statement** is the result of the signed statement being placed on the ledger, and notarized with a counter signature

All we're proposing here is converging terminology, as changing the terminology from statement to claim infers it's more than furthering the statement along the workflow

@rjb4standards, those are great questions. I'd just suggest we focus on the convergence of the terminology here. 
 For the purposes of this issue, the issuer creates a statement about an artifact. It gets signed (signed statement), and placed on the ledger (transparent statement). 
If the user simply wants to get a notarized statement that the `net-monitor:v1` software was issued by "wabbit-networks", the user can submit a statement to the registry that it was signed by wabbit-networks. There's no "evidence" or additional information provided, yet. It's simply a notarized statement that wabbit-networks submitted the artifact.

@fournet : Thank you for this. I think, we should start Threat Model as a separate document to begin with. The reason been, I expect Supply Chain Security been a complex subject the number of threats and mitigation strategies will be a long document.

I would prefer a pointer to the document from the master Architecture document, then!

Once the document is in final shape post Community review, at that time we can make a final call, should we merge it to Main Arch. Doc or leave it separate.
